  "slug": "king-prawn-balti",
  "title": "King prawn balti",
  "subtitle": "Fast, fragrant prawn curry in the Birmingham balti tradition",
  "excerpt": "King prawns cooked quickly in a spiced tomato and pepper sauce in a steel balti dish over high heat. The balti technique is defined by speed (the whole dish cooks in under 15 minutes once the sauce is ready) and by the heat of the steel pan, which gives the sauce a slight char and intensity. A Birmingham curry-mile original, now a staple across the British Indian menu.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The balti curry style was developed in Birmingham's Sparkhill and Sparkbrook areas (the 'Balti Triangle') from the late 1970s. The term refers to the steel wok-like vessel in which the food is cooked and served. Widely adopted across British Indian menus by the 1990s, particularly with seafood.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The balti technique relies on a very hot pan and a short cook. Prawns go from raw to overcooked in about 4 minutes once heat is applied. They are ready when they have turned from grey-translucent to pink-opaque and just curled. If they continue past that point, they tighten further, release moisture, and become rubbery. Watch them, not the clock.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A traditional balti includes a combination of whole and ground spices added in stages: whole spices first in hot oil for fragrance, then ground spices with the tomato base. The peppers and onion are kept slightly firm rather than cooked to softness, the balti should have textural presence, not be a smooth sauce with prawns in it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
