      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the sauce base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide heavy pan or wok over high heat until shimmering. Add the {{cumin-seeds}} and fry for 20 seconds. Add the {{onion}}, {{pepper-red}}, and {{pepper-green}} and cook for 5 minutes, stirring, until softened but still with some texture. Add the {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{chilli-green}}, {{turmeric}}, {{cumin-ground}}, {{coriander-ground}}, and {{chilli-powder}} and stir for 1 minute. Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}} and cook for 8 minutes until reduced to a thick, fragrant sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the prawns and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{king-prawns}} to the sauce. Toss to coat and cook over high heat for 3 to 4 minutes, stirring frequently, until the prawns are pink and just cooked through. Stir in the {{garam-masala}} and season with salt. Scatter over fresh coriander if using. Serve immediately, balti is a dish that waits for no one.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Prawns are done when they turn pink and just curl. Remove from heat as soon as that happens, carryover heat continues the cooking",
              "cause": "Overcooked",
              "symptom": "Prawns rubbery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce the tomato sauce to a very thick paste before adding the prawns. The prawns release liquid; the sauce must be thick enough to absorb it without becoming thin",
              "cause": "Prawns released moisture into a thin sauce",
              "symptom": "Sauce watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "In balti cooking, vegetables should retain some bite. Remove from heat while still slightly firm. They will soften further in the sauce",
              "cause": "Peppers and onion cooked too soft",
              "symptom": "No textural contrast"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Get the pan as hot as possible before adding the cumin seeds. The characteristic intensity comes from cooking over very high heat throughout",
              "cause": "Heat not high enough",
              "symptom": "Lacks the charred intensity of restaurant balti"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The balti is one of the few British additions to the global Indian restaurant menu. The style started in Birmingham and spread out to the rest of the UK before reaching the wider world. Balti houses in the Balti Triangle serve the food in the same steel pot it was cooked in, set on the table with naan for scooping. The prawn version is one of the most popular. The quick cook suits seafood well, and the high-heat charring of the sauce gives it a depth that slow-cooked prawn curries cannot match.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
